<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-911-842  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 911 842.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  Oct 19 1989 n1186 p11(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Bedsit outlaws say carry on hacking. (hackers' attitudes towardthe British Law Commission proposal to outlaw hacking)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Collins, Tony.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The British Law Commission proposed to make computer hackingpunishable by up to five years imprisonment.andP;  One group ofhackers, however, is not too concerned; a spokesperson with thecode name Frostbyte commented that hackers 'hack' because they arenot supposed to.andP;  The law, therefore, might give them addedincentive to tamper with computer systems.andP;  Computer hackersthrive on acquiring notoriety, and even computer professionals whodisapprove may secretly admire hackers' skills.andP;  In someinstances, hackers merely have to get someone to tell them apassword.andP;  Other, more complicated instances, involve tamperingwith protection codes and creating pirate versions of software.andO;Frostbye says that his group also accesses AT andamp; T illegally.andO;Although the Federation Against Software Theft knows Frostbyte andhis cohorts' names, they cannot prosecute without catching thehackers red-handed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer HackersFraudSecurity SystemsGreat Britain. Law CommissionFederation Against Software TheftLegislationEnglandComputer Crimes.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>